  "answer": "The argument first turns toward intellectual property in Vol II, Chapter 28 ('De quelques espèces de propriétés commerciales'), slug: charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5. Having established in chapters 27-28 that property arises from labor that adds utility to matter, Comte pivots at paragraph [p-d29938] by noting that 'civilized peoples' place 'certain conceptions of the mind' — literary and scientific works, musical compositions, drawings, and industrial inventions — in the rank of properties, and raises the question whether this is truly justified or merely 'a sort of abuse.' The chapter then works through reputation and goodwill as quasi-IP analogs and closes with the explicit announcement at [p-700447]: 'It remains to examine whether certain conceptions of the mind, when they have been realized, ought to be placed in the rank of properties.'\n\nChapter 29 ('De la propriété des inventions ou des procédés industriels', chapter_number 29) immediately executes this turn. Comte begins by tracing the historical analogy between occupying unowned land and 'discovering' an industrial art, then critiques the French Constituent Assembly's decree proclaiming that every invention 'is the property of its author' by natural right. The decisive analytical move arrives at paragraph [p-d81732]: Comte distinguishes sharply between (1) the right to *exploit* one's own invention — uncontroversial, requiring no special law, secured by general liberty — and (2) the right to *prevent others from exploiting the same art* — a genuine monopoly, not derivable from the natural-property principle, requiring a specific legal grant. He argues that the Constituent Assembly confused these two rights and that the 'occupation' principle applicable to material things (land, wild animals) cannot coherently extend to mental processes, because exercising an art by one person is no obstacle to others exercising the same art. Chapter 29 thus reframes industrial IP from a natural property claim to a time-limited monopoly justifiable, at best, by utilitarian encouragement, not by inherent rights.",
