**Summary of findings:**

The turn toward intellectual property in Vol II of the *Traité de la propriété* unfolds across two chapters:

**Chapter 28** (the pivot): After developing the general movable-property theory through labor and utility, Comte first raises "conceptions of the mind" — literary works, inventions, musical compositions — as puzzling edge cases at **[p-d29938]**. He spends the rest of the chapter on reputation and goodwill as quasi-IP analogs, then closes at **[p-700447]** with the announcement: *"It remains to examine whether certain conceptions of the mind, when they have been realized, ought to be placed in the rank of properties."*

**Chapter 29** (the execution): The decisive analytical move is the distinction at **[p-d81732]** between two fundamentally different rights: (1) the right to *exploit* one's own invention — grounded in general liberty, requiring no special law — and (2) the right to *prevent others from doing the same* — a genuine monopoly requiring specific legal authorization. Comte uses this to demolish the Constituent Assembly's natural-rights theory of invention-property: since one person practicing an art is no obstacle to others doing the same, the "occupation" principle cannot coherently apply. Industrial IP is thereby reframed from a natural right into a time-limited, utilitarian monopoly at best.
